#Ok, since my steps seem to work might as well make them reusable with functions:

def get_data(stocks,start_date,end_date):

  df = yf.download(
      tickers=stocks,
      start=start_date,
      end=end_date,
      interval="1d",
      group_by="ticker",
      auto_adjust=True,
      progress=False
  )
  return df.xs("Close",axis=1,level="Price")

def compute_CAGR(df_close,start_date,end_date):
  days= (end_date-start_date).days
  n=days/365
  V_i=df_close.iloc[0]
  V_f=df_close.iloc[-1]
  return ((V_f)/(V_i))**(1/n)-1

def compute_returns(df_close):
  return df_close.pct_change()

def compute_volatility(returns):
  return returns.std()

def compute_correlation(df_close):
  return df_close.corr()

#Lets add some finance specific metrics:
#Sharpe Ratio
"""
If I understand the Sharpe Ratio correctly, it measures the extra returns you get from assuming risk. So if I have 2 options for mfilling in my portfolio:
Add investments on a treasury bond which is basically 0 risk or add investments on something that is non-zero risk, how much more do I earn if
I add any risk to my portfolio?

[(Portfolio with Risk Return)-(Risk-Free Return)]/(Standard Deviation of Portfolio Excess Returns)
"""

"""
Following that idea:
Sharp Ratio = [(Rp)-(Rf)]/(SDp)

-My daily returns from "compute returns" would be Rp
-For Rf we assume the returns of a risk free assets of treasury bills or bonds.
I prefer using bills given they are short term so less prone to be affected by macro scenarios. Especially with today´s
administration (Yikes).
According to Bloomberg.com (So yes, im getting the composite of trasury bills not a real yield since I want the general case),
 3 month and 12 month bills have both a yield of 3.67% (Huh, interesting. ). Those are
tickers GB3:GOV nad GB12:GOV respectively. The 6 month one gives 3.7% so it holds, we´ll use the 12 month yield of 3.67%.
I could get the data for bonds and bills from FRED but I dont want to complicate myself too much.
"""
rp=compute_returns(df_close).mean()
#print(rp)
rf=0.037

SD= compute_volatility(compute_returns(df_close))
#print(SD)

#Now all but rf are daily numbers. So we can convert all to either daily or yearly. Will do all to daily.
rf0=0.0367 #Alright, thats annual ratio and we have 252 trading days
"""
ra will be annual risk rate, and rd will be daily risk rate (goal)
We know: ra=1+0.0367
And: ra=(1+rd)**(252)
thus: 1+0.0367=(1+rd)**(252)
root of 252: (1+0.0367)**(1/252)=1+rd
so: 1.0367**(1/252)-1=rd
Thus we have rd.
Will become our new rf.
"""
rf=(1+rf0)**(1/252)-1
print("Risk free return: ", rf)


sharpe_ratio=(rp-rf)/SD

print(sharpe_ratio)

annualized_sharpe=(sharpe_ratio)*(252**(1/2))
print("The annualized ratios are: ", annualized_sharpe)

